      "title": "Results and Interpretations",
      "cols": [
        "Finding / Observation",
        "Description",
        "General Interpretation / Significance"
      ],
      "rows": [
        [
          "Normal scan",
          " No abnormalities detected in arteries, veins, or surrounding tissues  ",
          "Vessels are healthy; no evidence of disease or vascular abnormality "
        ],
        [
          "Abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA)",
          "Localized enlargement of the abdominal aorta (>3 cm diameter)   ",
          "Risk of rupture increases with size; may require monitoring or surgery"
        ],
        [
          "Renal artery stenosis",
          "Narrowing of one or both renal arteries, often with reduced kidney perfusion",
          "Can cause hypertension or kidney dysfunction; may need intervention "
        ],
        [
          "Mesenteric artery occlusion",
          "Blockage in the superior or inferior mesenteric artery, sometimes with bowel wall thickening",
          "Suggests acute or chronic mesenteric ischemia; urgent evaluation needed"
        ],
        [
          "Portal vein thrombosis",
          "Blood clot within the portal venous system, sometimes with collateral vessel formation ",
          " May lead to portal hypertension; requires further investigation"
        ]
      ]
    },
    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "Is CT ANGIO ABDOMEN painful?",
        "answer": " No. You may feel warm during contrast injection, but it lasts seconds.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "How long does the whole visit take? ",
        "answer": "Plan 60 minutes: 15 min prep, 15 min scan, 30 min observation & discharge."
      },
      {
        "question": "Can I drive home after the test? ",
        "answer": " Yes, unless you took a sedative (rarely needed).\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Will I need follow-up scans? ",
        "answer": " Your doctor will decide based on findings. Stable aneurysms may be monitored annually.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "What happens if an abnormality like an aneurysm is found?  ",
        "answer": "If your scan reveals a significant abnormality like a large **aortic aneurysm**, your referring doctor will be notified promptly. They will discuss the findings with you in detail and create a management plan. This may involve regular monitoring with repeat scans or a referral to a specialist, such as a vascular surgeon, to discuss treatment options."
      }
    ],
